stice by police. In this book, Robert E. Worden and Sarah J. McLean argue that the procedural justice model of reform is a mirage. From a distance, procedural justice seemingly offers a relief from strained police-community relations. But a closer look at police organizations and police-citizen interactions shows that the relief offered by such reform is, in fact, illusory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh1 aMcLean, Sarah J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066755440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965966?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965966zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965966/original  a978-3-11-066755-4 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA